    "summary": "After completing my graduate studies at the Vrije Universiteit van Amsterdam, I did a PhD on regional geology, which focussed on fore arc tectonics in Indonesia at the Netherlands Institute for Sea Research. This was followed by a post doc at the Geological Survey of Japan, where I studied back arc evolution along the eastern Japan Sea.\n\n A second post doc at the University of Liverpool dealt with clastic turbidite fan systems in the Karoo (South Africa). Finally, a third post doc was conducted at the University of Brunei, where I worked with a 3D seismic volume covering the continental slope. \n\nI firmly entered the oil industry after landing at Shell, where I worked for 6 years. Initially, I spent three years at Rijswijk (The Netherlands) where I became involved in New Venture Projects in Africa (Mozambique, Tunisia and Nigeria). This was followed by an assignment at Shell Brunei (BSP), where I worked on deep water projects (regional framework studies, prospect mapping, volumetrics and risking and ranking of toe thrust turbidite prospects). \n\nI subsequently moved to Petronas Brunei, where I had the opportunity to be involved in maturing and drilling related deep water prospects in the neighbouring exploration blocks. By doing so, I completed an exploration cycle and evolved from a turbidite geologist into a deep water explorationist. \n\nDuring my final two year job assignment with Genel Energy, I was engaged in frontier hydrocarbon evaluation projects, which addressed the regional geological history of Somaliland, Ethiopia as well as western Morocco. I was also involved in the evaluation of farm-in projects in Mongolia, Kenya, Guinea, Guinea Bissau, Senegal and the Canary Islands.\n\nMy interests range from exposure and involvement with different cultures, religions, languages,  sport (hockey) and exotic asian kitchen flavours.",
